HEADWORD: Hebraism
<hw>He"bra*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>h⟦eacute⟧bra⟦ium⟧sme</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A Hebrew idiom or custom; a peculiar expression or
manner of speaking in the Hebrew language.</def>
<rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The type of character of the Hebrews.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The governing idea of <qex>Hebraism</qex> is strictness of
conscience.</q> <rj><qau>M. Arnold.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hebraist</ent>⟦br⟧
